Loading the files from the zip

options(timeout = 6000)
download.file("https://ethz-ins.org/content/w10.assignment.zip", "w10.practical.zip")
unzip("w10.practical.zip")
list.files()
##  [1] "assignment_files"  "assignment.html"   "assignment.Rmd"   
##  [4] "Creb1.bed"         "Creb1.bw"          "Creb3.bed"        
##  [7] "Creb3.bw"          "Creb3L1.bed"       "Creb3L1.bw"       
## [10] "w10.practical.zip"
# importing the two files 
tracks <- list.files(pattern="bw$")

regions <- list.files(pattern="bed$")


# we first import the peaks
peaks <- lapply(regions, rtracklayer::import.bed)
# we'll focus on the high-quality peaks
peaks <- lapply(peaks, FUN=function(x) x[x$score>800])
# we get the union of non-redundant regions
regions <- reduce(unlist(GRangesList(peaks)))


#plotting the signal to matrix 
ml <- signal2Matrix(tracks, regions, extend=2000)
## Reading Creb1.bw
## Reading Creb3.bw
## Reading Creb3L1.bw
set.seed(123)  # to ensure that it gives the same results everytime
nf <- getNormFactors(tracks, useSeqLevels="chr1")
## Comparing coverage in random regions...
ml <- rescaleSignalMatrices(ml, scaleFactors=nf)

plotEnrichedHeatmaps(ml)

Clustering

set.seed(123)

cl2 <- clusterSignalMatrices(ml, k=2:10) # plotting the clusters from 2 to 10, here can see on the graph the ideal number 
ggplot(cl2$varExplained, aes(k, varExplained)) + geom_line()

# here choose the ideal cluster type 
cl <- clusterSignalMatrices(ml, k=5)
##   ~72% of the variance explained by clusters
d <- meltSignals(ml, splitBy=cl)
ggplot(d, aes(position, mean, colour=sample)) + geom_line(size=1.2) + facet_wrap(~split)
## Warning: Using `size` aesthetic for lines was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.

split_regions <- split(regions, cl)

job <- submitGreatJob(gr=split_regions[["5"]], bg=regions, species="hg38")
## Warning: From rGREAT 1.99.0, `bg` will not be supported any more because GREAT
